    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "act": "COLD OPEN \u2014 title/hook",
      "t_start": 0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Give two electrons parallel spins and they keep their distance \u2014 even though nothing in the equations pushes them apart.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "fade"
      },
      "card": {
        "chip": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "title": "Why Two Electrons Avoid Each Other With No Force",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 6.5,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/clips/B01.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "act": "COLD OPEN \u2014 concrete case (oxygen is magnetic)",
      "t_start": 9,
      "estimated_duration_s": 16,
      "narration_text": "Oxygen has two electrons in its outer shell with the same spin direction. They spread apart, lower the atom's energy, and make oxygen a magnet.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.91,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "act": "COLD OPEN \u2014 the puzzle",
      "t_start": 25,
      "estimated_duration_s": 14,
      "narration_text": "The electrons feel no special repulsion from spin. The Hamiltonian has no spin-spin force term. Something else is keeping them apart.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.59,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "act": "THE QUESTION",
      "t_start": 39,
      "estimated_duration_s": 15,
      "narration_text": "Parallel-spin electrons sit farther apart and cost less energy. No force pushes them. Why does their spin direction control their separation?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "fade"
      },
      "card": {
        "chip": "THE QUESTION",
        "title": "Spin controls separation. No force does it. Why?",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.8,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM \u2014 naive picture fails",
      "t_start": 54,
      "estimated_duration_s": 17,
      "narration_text": "You might guess spin-up and spin-down repel each other, like magnets. But electrons' magnetic moments are tiny \u2014 too weak to move them apart at atomic scales.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.04,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM \u2014 indistinguishability",
      "t_start": 71,
      "estimated_duration_s": 18,
      "narration_text": "The real constraint is deeper: two electrons have no individual identity. When their clouds overlap there is no fact about which is which \u2014 only one combined wavefunction.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.06,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/clips/B06.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM \u2014 antisymmetry forces a node",
      "t_start": 89,
      "estimated_duration_s": 20,
      "narration_text": "Fermions need an antisymmetric wavefunction. For parallel spins the spin part is symmetric, so the spatial part must be antisymmetric \u2014 and that function must equal zero wherever both electrons coincide.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.14,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/clips/B07.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM \u2014 the joint probability map",
      "t_start": 109,
      "estimated_duration_s": 20,
      "narration_text": "Map joint probability over the two positions. Parallel spins carve a node along the diagonal \u2014 electrons can never be at the same spot. Opposite spins pile up there instead.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.48,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/clips/B08.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B08.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM \u2014 Coulomb consequence",
      "t_start": 129,
      "estimated_duration_s": 18,
      "narration_text": "Farther apart means less Coulomb repulsion. Less repulsion means lower energy. The antisymmetric state is cheaper \u2014 no force required, just geometry of the wavefunction.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.1,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/clips/B09.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B09.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "act": "THE IMPLICATION \u2014 Hund's rule and oxygen",
      "t_start": 147,
      "estimated_duration_s": 19,
      "narration_text": "This is Hund's rule: fill each orbital with one parallel-spin electron before pairing. The exchange effect stabilizes the high-spin state. That is why oxygen is paramagnetic.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.73,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/clips/B10.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B10.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "act": "THE EXAMPLE (illustrative)",
      "t_start": 166,
      "estimated_duration_s": 22,
      "narration_text": "Suppose you have two electrons in a one-dimensional box, parallel spins. Their joint probability map has a node on the diagonal \u2014 they're never found at the same position. Flip one spin, the node disappears, they bunch up, energy rises by roughly 0.80 eV in helium.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "example_note": "illustrative",
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 17.4,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/clips/B11.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B11.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "act": "RECAP",
      "t_start": 188,
      "estimated_duration_s": 18,
      "narration_text": "Parallel-spin electrons avoid each other because antisymmetry carves a node at coincidence \u2014 less Coulomb energy, no force needed. That is the exchange effect.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "fade"
      },
      "card": {
        "chip": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "title": "Antisymmetry carves a node. No force needed.",
        "dek": "The exchange effect"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.263,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/clips/B12.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-avoidance/mp3/beat-B12.mp3"
    },
